<br>
When you run into the .dll error, it means that Everquest is conflicting with itself, perhaps because of the way your computer is set up.  it's not designed to be run in two instances... some computer setups might just allow it, others might not. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=rainik6>Rainik6</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 575<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/28/03 4:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4817.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: My own two account one Comp question.</span><hr size=1> Win98 has different memory management so it works different on 98. Some say it works better. Anyway here are some general tips for any OS. <br>
<br>
Do not end you day of playing in pok or the bazaar. I can not do anything if one of my guys is in the bazaar. Also noticed that dawnshroud is bad with all the trees. <br>
<br>
Turn off spell effects, 3dsky, and if lots of lag turn off luclin models. <br>
<br>
Run both instances at same resolution and one behind the other. Dont run two side by side. <br>
<br>
Install EQ in two different directories and turn off sound in one of them by placing a txt file named nosound.txt in the main folder. <br>
